{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016DJa1JXray7QmTMDJwsLwQ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Nuclear Energy Investment Thesis\n2\t\n3\t**February 2026 | BigPic Research**\n4\t\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\t## Executive Summary\n8\t\n9\tNuclear energy is experiencing a structural renaissance driven by three converging forces: (1) insatiable AI/data center demand for 24/7 carbon-free baseload power, (2) the strongest US policy environment in decades (ADVANCE Act, IRA credits, NRC reform), and (3) a global supply chain in deep deficit across uranium, conversion, enrichment, and HALEU fuel.\n10\t\n11\tThe Big 5 hyperscalers have contracted **10+ GW of nuclear capacity** in the past year, committing over **$50B in long-term PPAs** to nuclear fleet operators. Existing nuclear plants operating at ~$30/MWh are selling 20-year contracts at $80-120/MWh to Microsoft, Meta, Amazon, and Google — a structural margin expansion that transforms historically volatile merchant generators into quasi-contracted infrastructure.\n12\t\n13\tSimultaneously, the uranium market faces a **30-40M lb annual supply deficit** with spot prices above $100/lb, the nuclear fuel cycle's conversion and enrichment stages are capacity-constrained, and Western nations are racing to break dependency on Russia's 46% enrichment monopoly. Advanced reactor developers (SMRs, molten salt, sodium-cooled) have attracted unprecedented funding but remain 4-8 years from commercial deployment.\n14\t\n15\t**Core thesis:** This is a multi-decade investment cycle spanning three layers — existing fleet operators (highest near-term visibility), fuel cycle companies (structural supply deficit), and next-gen technology developers (highest growth optionality but execution risk). Power availability is the binding constraint on AI infrastructure, and nuclear is the only scalable 24/7 carbon-free solution.\n16\t\n17\t---\n18\t\n19\t## Industry Overview & Market Size\n20\t\n21\t### The Nuclear Power Landscape\n22\t\n23\t| Metric | Value |\n24\t|--------|-------|\n25\t| US operating reactors | 93 at 54 sites |\n26\t| US nuclear share of electricity | ~20% |\n27\t| US nuclear share of carbon-free electricity | ~47% (largest source) |\n28\t| Global operating reactors | ~440 |\n29\t| Reactors under construction (global) | 63-68 (66-74 GWe) |\n30\t| Reactors planned (global) | 108 (~103 GWe) |\n31\t| Average US capacity factor | ~93.5% |\n32\t| Average operating cost (existing plants) | ~$31/MWh |\n33\t\n34\t### Market Size & Growth Drivers\n35\t\n36\t| Segment | 2025 Est. | 2030 Projection | Growth Driver |\n37\t|---------|-----------|-----------------|---------------|\n38\t| Data center electricity demand (US) | 183 TWh | 426 TWh (+133%) | AI infrastructure buildout |\n39\t| Global uranium demand | ~179M lbs U3O8 | ~200M+ lbs | New reactor construction |\n40\t| Uranium spot price | $85-100/lb | Consensus $100+ sustained | Supply deficit, Russian ban |\n41\t| SMR investment (global) | ~$5B | $25B+ (IEA) | First commercial deployments |\n42\t| Hyperscaler nuclear PPAs | $50B+ contracted | Growing | Power demand outpacing grid |\n43\t| COP28 nuclear target | Baseline | Triple capacity by 2050 | 28+ countries committed |\n44\t\n45\t### AI-Driven Power Demand\n46\t\n47\tGlobal data center electricity demand is projected to more than double from 460 TWh (2024) to over 1,000 TWh by 2030. Nuclear currently supplies ~20% of US data center electricity. Hyperscalers require 99.999% uptime and growing GW-scale loads — nuclear's 93%+ capacity factor and 24/7 profile make it the only generation source that can reliably meet this demand without intermittency or massive storage overbuild.\n48\t\n49\t---\n50\t\n51\t## Key Sectors\n52\t\n53\t### 1. Nuclear Utilities & Fleet Operators\n54\t\n55\tThe existing US nuclear fleet is being repriced as irreplaceable infrastructure. No new large-scale nuclear plants can be built in the US within a decade (Vogtle took 14 years and $35B). The four publicly traded fleet operators — Constellation Energy, Vistra, Talen Energy, and PSEG — have locked in multi-decade contracts with the world's most creditworthy counterparties.\n56\t\n57\t**Hyperscaler Nuclear Deals (Announced 2024-2026)**\n58\t\n59\t| Hyperscaler | Partner | Plant/Technology | Capacity | Term | Est. Value |\n60\t|-------------|---------|------------------|----------|------|------------|\n61\t| Microsoft | Constellation | TMI Unit 1 (restart) | 835 MW | 20 yr | ~$16B |\n62\t| Meta | Constellation | Clinton (IL) | 1,121 MW | 20 yr | N/A |\n63\t| Meta | Vistra | Perry, Davis-Besse, Beaver Valley + 433MW uprates | 2,609 MW | 20 yr | N/A |\n64\t| Meta | Oklo | New build (Pike County, OH) | 1,200 MW | N/A | N/A |\n65\t| Meta | TerraPower | Natrium reactors | 690 MW initial, 2.8 GW total | N/A | N/A |\n66\t| Amazon | Talen | Susquehanna (PA) | 1,920 MW | 17 yr | ~$18B |\n67\t| Google | Kairos Power | SMR fleet | 500 MW | N/A | N/A |\n68\t| Undisclosed | Vistra | Comanche Peak (TX) | 1,200 MW | 20 yr | N/A |\n69\t\n70\t**Fleet Expansion Catalysts:**\n71\t- NRC approving 80-year license extensions (Peach Bottom approved March 2025; 13 renewals in 2025)\n72\t- 6+ GW of capacity uprates under consideration (Meta-Vistra deal alone = 433 MW)\n73\t- Plant restarts: TMI Unit 1 (835 MW, target 2027-28), Palisades (800 MW, target early 2026)\n74\t- Executive Order directing 5 GW of uprates and 10 new large reactors by 2030\n75\t\n76\t**Nuclear Plant Economics:**\n77\t- Operating cost: ~$30/MWh (merchant plants ~$28/MWh)\n78\t- Hyperscaler PPA rates: estimated $80-120/MWh\n79\t- Capacity factor: 93%+ (Constellation achieved 98.8% in Summer 2025)\n80\t- Fuel cost: ~15-20% of total operating cost\n81\t- Margin expansion: plants that were marginally economic at $25-35/MWh wholesale are now generating massive margins\n82\t\n83\t### 2. Uranium Mining & Fuel Cycle\n84\t\n85\tThe uranium market is in a structural deficit unlikely to resolve before end of decade. Primary mine supply covers ~75% of global reactor requirements, secondary sources (inventories, underfeeding) are at historic lows, and every stage of the fuel cycle faces capacity constraints.\n86\t\n87\t**Supply-Demand Fundamentals:**\n88\t\n89\t| Metric | Value |\n90\t|--------|-------|\n91\t| Uranium spot price (Jan 2026 peak) | ~$100/lb U3O8 |\n92\t| Long-term contract price | $75-85/lb (Cameco targeting $130-140 ceilings) |\n93\t| Annual reactor demand | ~179M lbs U3O8 |\n94\t| Annual mine production | ~140-150M lbs |\n95\t| Annual supply gap | ~30-40M lbs |\n96\t| By 2035, mines cover | Only 40% of demand |\n97\t\n98\t**Conversion Bottleneck:**\n99\tOnly 4 major Western conversion facilities operating at ~91% utilization. Buffer inventories depleted. 5.5-7.7% CAGR in requirements through 2040.\n100\t\n101\t**Enrichment Geopolitics:**\n102\tRussia controls ~46% of global enrichment capacity (27M SWU/yr). US ban on Russian enriched uranium effective 2028. Western expansion: Urenco adding 2.5M SWU globally, Centrus awarded $900M for commercial-scale HALEU. Gap will take 5-7 years to fully close.\n103\t\n104\t**Key Producers:**\n105\t\n106\t| Company | Ticker | Production (2025-26) | Key Catalyst |\n107\t|---------|--------|---------------------|-------------|\n108\t| Kazatomprom | KAP | 27.5-29K tU (2026, ~10% below capacity) | Production discipline = price support |\n109\t| Cameco | CCJ | Up to 20M lbs (McArthur cuts tighten supply) | Rising contract prices (+5-10% in 2026) |\n110\t| NexGen Energy | NXE | Development (30M lbs/yr capacity) | CNSC hearing Feb 2026 |\n111\t| Denison Mines | DNN | Construction-ready Q1 2026 | First Athabasca ISR mine |\n112\t| Uranium Energy Corp | UEC | Ramping ISR production | Burke Hollow + Christensen Ranch |\n113\t| Energy Fuels | UUUU | >1M lbs (2025) + rare earth pivot | Dual uranium/REE play |\n114\t| Centrus Energy | LEU | 900 kg/yr HALEU (pilot) | $900M DOE commercial expansion |\n115\t\n116\t### 3. SMRs & Advanced Nuclear Technology\n117\t\n118\tThe advanced nuclear sector is at a historic inflection point. Big tech has signed 10+ GW of commitments. The ADVANCE Act cut NRC fees 50%+ for advanced reactors. DOE has committed $6B+ in funding. However, most pure-play companies remain pre-revenue with first commercial units 4-8 years away.\n119\t\n120\t**Technology Status:**\n121\t\n122\t| Developer | Type | Capacity | Timeline | NRC Status | Key Backer |\n123\t|-----------|------|----------|----------|------------|------------|\n124\t| NuScale VOYGR | Light-water PWR | 77 MWe/module | 2029-2032 | Certified (2023) | TVA/ENTRA1 (6 GW MOU) |\n125\t| GE Hitachi BWRX-300 | Boiling water | 300 MWe | 2030 (Ontario) | Pre-application (US) | OPG, Synthos, SaskPower |\n126\t| Kairos Power Hermes | Molten salt-cooled | 35 MWt (demo) | 2026 (demo) | Construction permit | Google (500 MW) |\n127\t| TerraPower Natrium | Sodium-cooled fast | 345-500 MWe | 2030 | CP expected Q1 2026 | Bill Gates, DOE |\n128\t| Oklo Aurora | Fast reactor | 15-50 MWe | 2030+ | Re-application | Sam Altman, Meta (1.2 GW) |\n129\t| X-energy Xe-100 | HTGR | 80 MWe | 2030+ | Application filed | Amazon (5+ GW), Dow |\n130\t| BWXT Pele | Micro HTGR | 1.5+ MWe | 2028 | DOD pathway | US military |\n131\t\n132\t**UAMPS Cautionary Tale:** NuScale's first project cancelled in 2023 after costs jumped from $5.3B to $9.3B (+75%). FOAK cost premiums are real — current SMR LCOE estimates of $95-110/MWh must prove through actual builds.\n133\t\n134\t**Fusion (Venture-Stage):**\n135\t- Commonwealth Fusion Systems: ~$3B raised, SPARC operational 2026, net power target 2027\n136\t- Helion Energy: Microsoft PPA for 50+ MW by 2028, Sam Altman backing\n137\t- TAE Technologies: $6B TMTG merger announced Dec 2025\n138\t\n139\t### 4. Policy & Regulatory Environment\n140\t\n141\t**US Policy Stack:**\n142\t- **ADVANCE Act (2024):** NRC fees cut 50%+, 18-month licensing deadlines, foreign ownership liberalization\n143\t- **IRA Credits:** Section 45U (1.5¢/kWh for existing plants through 2032), Section 45X (manufacturing)\n144\t- **Executive Order 14300:** Comprehensive NRC reform with binding deadlines, Part 53 framework for advanced reactors (final rule March 2026)\n145\t- **DOE Loan Programs:** Nuclear is \"by far the biggest use\" — Palisades ($1.52B), TMI ($1B), FY2026 requesting $30B in new Title 17 authority\n146\t- **Russian Uranium Ban:** Effective 2028, unlocked $2.72B for domestic enrichment investment\n147\t\n148\t**Global Buildout:**\n149\t\n150\t| Country | Program | Scale | Timeline |\n151\t|---------|---------|-------|----------|\n152\t| China | Hualong One batch production | 150+ reactors to 200 GW by 2035 | 10 approved April 2025 (~$27.5B) |\n153\t| UK | Sizewell C (EPR) | 2 units, GBP 38B (~$51B) | FID signed July 2025 |\n154\t| France | EPR2 revival | 6 reactors + SMR pipeline | EUR 50B program |\n155\t| India | Nuclear Energy Mission | 100 GW by 2047 | From 8.2 GW today |\n156\t| South Korea | APR-1400 exports | Barakah success = marketing credential | Czech tender pursuit |\n157\t| Saudi Arabia | Civil nuclear | 2 reactors + domestic enrichment | US cooperation framework signed Nov 2025 |\n158\t\n159\t**Key Risk: NRC Staffing.** ~195 employees departed since Jan 2025, including 11 senior managers. Federal hiring freeze compounds the problem. The NRC faces its most ambitious workload in decades with a shrinking workforce — this is arguably the single biggest near-term bottleneck for US nuclear deployment.\n160\t\n161\t---\n162\t\n163\t## Public Company Analysis\n164\t\n165\t### Fleet Operators\n166\t\n167\t| Company | Ticker | Market Cap | Fwd P/E | Nuclear GW | EV/Nuclear GW | Key Deal | 2026E Growth |\n168\t|---------|--------|-----------|---------|-----------|---------------|----------|-------------|\n169\t| Constellation Energy | CEG | ~$90B | ~31x | 22.6 GW | ~$4.0B/GW | TMI+Clinton (MSFT, Meta) | ~21% EPS |\n170\t| Vistra Corp | VST | ~$50B | ~14-16x | 6.4 GW | ~$7.8B/GW | Meta 2,609 MW + uprates | ~73-93% earnings |\n171\t| Talen Energy | TLN | ~$15B | N/A | 2.5 GW | ~$6.0B/GW | Amazon $18B/17yr | Strong Buy consensus |\n172\t| PSEG | PEG | ~$40B | N/A | 3.6 GW | ~$11.1B/GW | Exploring hyperscaler deals | Hold/Buy |\n173\t\n174\t### Fuel Cycle\n175\t\n176\t| Company | Ticker | Market Cap | Role | Key Metric |\n177\t|---------|--------|-----------|------|-----------|\n178\t| Cameco | CCJ | ~$25B+ | #2 uranium miner | 20M lbs guidance, rising contract prices |\n179\t| Kazatomprom | KAP | ~$15B+ | #1 uranium miner (40% global) | 10% below capacity = price discipline |\n180\t| Centrus Energy | LEU | ~$4B+ | Only Western HALEU producer | $900M DOE expansion award |\n181\t| NexGen Energy | NXE | ~$5B+ | Largest development-stage mine | CNSC hearing Feb 2026 |\n182\t| Denison Mines | DNN | ~$2B+ | Wheeler River ISR development | Construction-ready Q1 2026, $700M+ war chest |\n183\t| Uranium Energy Corp | UEC | ~$3B+ | Largest US-focused producer | ISR ramp-up across 3 platforms |\n184\t| Energy Fuels | UUUU | ~$2B+ | Only US conventional mill + REE | >1M lbs U3O8 in 2025, rare earth pivot |\n185\t\n186\t### Advanced Nuclear / SMR\n187\t\n188\t| Company | Ticker | Market Cap | Revenue | Key Asset |\n189\t|---------|--------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n190\t| BWX Technologies | BWXT | ~$14B | $764M/qtr | $6B backlog, Navy reactor monopoly |\n191\t| NuScale Power | SMR | ~$5B | $37M (2024) | Only NRC-certified SMR, 6 GW TVA MOU |\n192\t| Oklo | OKLO | ~$11B | $0 | 1.2 GW Meta deal, fuel recycling IP |\n193\t\n194\t### Physical Uranium & ETFs\n195\t\n196\t| Vehicle | Ticker | AUM/Holdings | Key Feature |\n197\t|---------|--------|-------------|-------------|\n198\t| Sprott Physical Uranium Trust | SRUUF/U.UN | 78.4M lbs (~$7.3B) | Structural spot buyer, largest physical fund |\n199\t| Global X Uranium ETF | URA | ~$5.0B | Broadest exposure, 50 companies |\n200\t| Sprott Uranium Miners ETF | URNM | Smaller | Purer uranium play, 11.6% physical allocation |\n201\t\n202\t---\n203\t\n204\t## Investment Timing Framework\n205\t\n206\t### Near-Term (0-12 months)\n207\t\n208\t| Catalyst | Timeline | Impact |\n209\t|----------|----------|--------|\n210\t| NexGen CNSC hearing | Feb 9-13, 2026 | Largest new uranium mine approval |\n211\t| Palisades restart | Feb-Mar 2026 | First US plant reactivated from decommissioning |\n212\t| TerraPower construction permit | Q1 2026 | Validates NRC reform timeline |\n213\t| Part 53 final rule | March 27, 2026 | Technology-inclusive licensing framework |\n214\t| NRC microreactor proposed rule | March 2026 | Enables defense/remote deployment |\n215\t| Vistra-Meta deliveries begin | Late 2026 | First hyperscaler nuclear PPA revenue |\n216\t| Urenco LEU+ production | Mid-2026 | First Western enriched LEU+ |\n217\t\n218\t### Mid-Term (1-3 years)\n219\t\n220\t| Catalyst | Timeline | Impact |\n221\t|----------|----------|--------|\n222\t| TMI Unit 1 restart | 2027-2028 | 835 MW back online for Microsoft |\n223\t| Constellation-Meta Clinton begins | June 2027 | 1,121 MW + 30 MW uprate |\n224\t| Kairos Hermes demo operational | 2026-2027 | First non-LWR demo in 50+ years |\n225\t| Denison Phoenix first production | Mid-2028 | First Athabasca ISR mine |\n226\t| Vistra Comanche Peak full delivery | 2027-2032 | 1,200 MW for undisclosed buyer |\n227\t| Centrus commercial HALEU | 2029 | Breaks Russian HALEU monopoly |\n228\t| GE Hitachi BWRX-300 (Ontario) | 2030 | First North American SMR operational |\n229\t\n230\t### Long-Term (3-10 years)\n231\t\n232\t| Catalyst | Timeline | Impact |\n233\t|----------|----------|--------|\n234\t| TerraPower Natrium commercial ops | 2030 | Sodium-cooled fast reactor at scale |\n235\t| X-energy Xe-100 at Dow Seadrift | 2030+ | HTGR industrial deployment |\n236\t| First commercial SMR fleet | 2030-2035 | NOAK cost reduction proof point |\n237\t| Meta-Oklo first phase | ~2030 | 1.2 GW new nuclear in Ohio |\n238\t| Amazon X-energy 5+ GW | By 2039 | Largest single nuclear commitment |\n239\t| Global nuclear capacity triple | By 2050 | COP28 commitment, 28+ countries |\n240\t| Commonwealth Fusion ARC plant | 2030s | First commercial fusion (if achieved) |\n241\t\n242\t---\n243\t\n244\t## Risk Factors\n245\t\n246\t### High Impact\n247\t\n248\t1. **Construction cost escalation** — Vogtle ($14B → $35B) and UAMPS ($5.3B → $9.3B cancelled) demonstrate that nuclear cost overruns are the norm, not the exception. FOAK premiums are severe.\n249\t\n250\t2. **NRC staffing crisis** — ~195 departures since Jan 2025 with a hiring freeze. The agency faces the most ambitious reform agenda in decades with a shrinking workforce. Licensing delays could cascade through the entire sector.\n251\t\n252\t3. **HALEU supply gap** — Current Western production: 900 kg/yr (Centrus pilot). Advanced reactors need orders of magnitude more. Commercial scale not expected until 2029+. Russia was the sole commercial source before sanctions.\n253\t\n254\t4. **Valuation risk in pre-revenue names** — Oklo at $11B and NuScale at $5B with zero/minimal revenue. Any execution setback could cause severe multiple compression.\n255\t\n256\t### Medium Impact\n257\t\n258\t5. **Hyperscaler demand moderation** — If AI capex slows or energy efficiency improves faster than expected, power demand growth could underperform projections.\n259\t\n260\t6. **Electricity price normalization** — If wholesale power prices decline, merchant nuclear margins compress (though 20-year PPAs mitigate for contracted fleet).\n261\t\n262\t7. **Uranium price volatility** — Kazatomprom could return to 100% production levels, government stockpile releases could temporarily depress spot prices.\n263\t\n264\t8. **Russian enrichment waivers extended** — Policy reversals on the uranium import ban could ease supply pressure on Western enrichment capacity.\n265\t\n266\t9. **SMR timeline slippage** — Most commercial SMR units are 4-8 years away. Advanced reactor designs (sodium, molten salt, HTGR) have never operated at commercial scale.\n267\t\n268\t### Structural / Long-Term\n269\t\n270\t10. **Nuclear waste policy** — 90,000 metric tons of spent fuel stored at reactor sites with no permanent disposal pathway. Yucca Mountain remains stalled. Interim storage facilities cleared by Supreme Court but face local opposition.\n271\t\n272\t11. **Competition from renewables + storage** — Solar + battery costs continue declining. For some applications, renewables may erode nuclear's economic case (though 24/7 firm power requirements increasingly favor nuclear).\n273\t\n274\t12. **Geopolitical fuel supply risk** — Russia + China could leverage nuclear fuel supply chains as strategic weapons. Western decoupling is underway but will take 5-7+ years.\n275\t\n276\t---\n277\t\n278\t## Recommended Watchlist\n279\t\n280\t### Tier 1 — Highest Conviction (Core Positions)\n281\t\n282\t| Ticker | Company | Thesis |\n283\t|--------|---------|--------|\n284\t| **CEG** | Constellation Energy | Largest nuclear fleet globally (22.6 GW), most hyperscaler relationships, Calpine acquisition creates 55 GW clean energy giant. Premium valuation justified by asset irreplaceability. |\n285\t| **VST** | Vistra Corp | Best value in fleet operators at ~14-16x fwd P/E with ~73-93% earnings growth in 2026. Meta deal provides 20-year revenue visibility. |\n286\t| **CCJ** | Cameco | Blue-chip uranium exposure, rising contract prices, production discipline. Safest way to play uranium supply deficit. |\n287\t| **LEU** | Centrus Energy | Only Western HALEU producer. $900M DOE expansion contract. Monopoly positioning in a strategically critical supply chain. |\n288\t\n289\t### Tier 2 — High Conviction (Growth Positions)\n290\t\n291\t| Ticker | Company | Thesis |\n292\t|--------|---------|--------|\n293\t| **TLN** | Talen Energy | $18B Amazon contract provides extraordinary revenue visibility. Single-asset risk but Strong Buy consensus. |\n294\t| **BWXT** | BWX Technologies | De-risked advanced nuclear play — $6B backlog, Navy reactor monopoly, profitable. Only way to play nuclear with real earnings. |\n295\t| **NXE** | NexGen Energy | Largest development-stage uranium project (30M lbs/yr). CNSC hearing Feb 2026 = near-term catalyst. |\n296\t| **UEC** | Uranium Energy Corp | Largest US-focused uranium producer, ISR ramp providing operating leverage to price. |\n297\t| **UUUU** | Energy Fuels | Dual uranium/rare earth optionality. Only operating US conventional uranium mill. |\n298\t\n299\t### Tier 3 — Speculative / Watchlist\n300\t\n301\t| Ticker | Company | Thesis |\n302\t|--------|---------|--------|\n303\t| **DNN** | Denison Mines | Wheeler River ISR, construction-ready Q1 2026, $700M+ war chest. High leverage to uranium price. |\n304\t| **OKLO** | Oklo | 1.2 GW Meta deal, fuel recycling IP, Sam Altman backing. Pre-revenue, $11B valuation = high risk. |\n305\t| **SMR** | NuScale Power | Only NRC-certified SMR. 6 GW TVA MOU. But UAMPS failure and pre-revenue status warrant caution. |\n306\t| **PEG** | PSEG | 3.6 GW fleet exploring hyperscaler deals. Regulated utility = lower volatility but less upside. |\n307\t| **SRUUF** | Sprott Uranium Trust | Direct physical uranium exposure. At-the-market buying supports spot price structurally. |\n308\t| **URA** | Global X Uranium ETF | Broadest uranium sector exposure for investors wanting diversified basket approach. |\n309\t\n310\t### Avoid / Wait\n311\t\n312\t| Ticker | Company | Reason |\n313\t|--------|---------|--------|\n314\t| Private: X-energy | — | Best-positioned private SMR developer (11 GW orderbook, $700M Series D) but no public equity access. Watch for IPO. |\n315\t| Private: Kairos Power | — | Google-backed, fastest demo progress. Wait for public listing. |\n316\t| Private: TerraPower | — | Bill Gates-backed, Natrium construction imminent. No equity access. |\n317\t| Fusion companies | CFS, Helion, TAE | Venture-stage bets. Binary outcomes, 5-10+ year timelines. Size as call options only. |\n318\t\n319\t---\n320\t\n321\t## Sources & References\n322\t\n323\t### Company Filings & Earnings\n324\t- [Constellation Q3 2025 Results](https://www.constellationenergy.com/newsroom/2025/11/constellation-reports-third-quarter-2025-results.html)\n325\t- [Constellation Q1 2025 Results](https://www.constellationenergy.com/newsroom/2025/constellation-reports-first-quarter-2025-results.html)\n326\t- [Constellation FY2024 Results](https://www.constellationenergy.com/newsroom/2025/constellation-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2024-results.html)\n327\t- [Vistra Q3 2025 Results](https://investor.vistracorp.com/2025-11-06-Vistra-Reports-Third-Quarter-2025-Results,-Narrows-2025-Guidance,-and-Initiates-2026-Guidance)\n328\t- [BWX Technologies Q3 2025 Results](https://investors.bwxt.com/news-releases/news-release-details/bwx-technologies-reports-third-quarter-2025-results)\n329\t- [Cameco Production Update](https://www.cameco.com/media/news/cameco-provides-production-update-strategically-well-positioned-for-continued-long-term)\n330\t- [Kazatomprom 1H2025 Results](https://www.kazatomprom.kz/en/media/view/1h2025_financial_results)\n331\t- [UEC Q1 FY2026 Results](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/uranium-energy-corp-reports-results-for-first-quarter-of-fiscal-2026-302637477.html)\n332\t- [Energy Fuels Year-End Production](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/energy-fuels-us-uranium-business-continues-to-deliver-with-year-end-production-and-sales-exceeding-guidance-302650065.html)\n333\t\n334\t### Hyperscaler Nuclear Deals\n335\t- [Constellation-Microsoft TMI Restart](https://www.constellationenergy.com/newsroom/2024/Constellation-to-Launch-Crane-Clean-Energy-Center-Restoring-Jobs-and-Carbon-Free-Power-to-The-Grid.html)\n336\t- [Constellation-Meta Clinton Deal](https://www.constellationenergy.com/newsroom/2025/constellation-meta-sign-20-year-deal-for-clean-reliable-nuclear-energy-in-illinois.html)\n337\t- [Meta 6.6 GW Nuclear Announcement](https://about.fb.com/news/2026/01/meta-nuclear-energy-pr