{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UpEebowQhmJAv8SUWv2ApW","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Rare Earth & Critical Minerals Investment Thesis\n2\t*Compiled: 2026-02-07*\n3\t*Source files: 01_Mining_Extraction.md, 02_Processing_Refining.md, 03_Defense_Demand.md, 04_China_Geopolitics.md*\n4\t\n5\t## Executive Summary\n6\t\n7\tThe critical minerals sector presents a generational investment opportunity driven by the convergence of three irreversible forces: the electrification of transportation and energy systems, the modernization of Western defense industrial bases, and the geopolitical fracturing of China-dominated supply chains. China controls approximately 60-70% of rare earth mining, 85-90% of processing, 92% of NdFeB permanent magnet manufacturing, and near-total monopolies on heavy rare earth separation (98%) and gallium refining (98%). Beijing has demonstrated its willingness to weaponize these dependencies through escalating export controls on gallium, germanium, antimony, rare earths, and tungsten since July 2023 -- triggering price spikes of 150-200% and forcing Western governments into a historic industrial mobilization exceeding $25 billion in combined allied investment.\n8\t\n9\tThe central tension for investors is timing versus valuation. Western rare earth and lithium equities have already rallied sharply (MP Materials +230% in 2025, Albemarle +90% from lows), pricing in substantial growth expectations. Yet the supply-demand fundamentals are structural: the IEA projects rare earth demand to nearly double by 2030 (driven by EVs, wind, and defense), copper faces a 150,000-330,000 tonne deficit starting in 2026, and lithium demand is projected to grow at 18% CAGR. The processing capacity gap -- Western facilities can meet only 10-12% of rare earth separation needs and 0% of heavy rare earth needs -- ensures that the companies building alternative supply chains will command strategic premiums for the next decade.\n10\t\n11\tThe key risk is China's ability to crash commodity prices to undermine Western investment economics, as it did in the 1990s to destroy the original Mountain Pass mine. The November 2025 temporary suspension of export controls may partly serve this purpose. Investors must balance the structural tailwind of supply chain reshoring against commodity price volatility, execution risk on complex processing projects, and the 5-15 year timeline to meaningful Western independence.\n12\t\n13\t## Industry Overview & Market Size\n14\t\n15\t### Critical Minerals Market Landscape (2025-2030)\n16\t\n17\t| Market | 2025 Size | 2030 Projection | CAGR | Primary Demand Driver |\n18\t|--------|-----------|-----------------|------|-----------------------|\n19\t| Rare Earth Elements | $7-14B | $15-25B | 8-13% | EV motors, wind turbines, defense, Chinese export controls |\n20\t| Lithium | ~$44B | ~$75B | ~18% | EV batteries, grid-scale energy storage |\n21\t| Copper | ~$250B+ | +$82B incremental | ~7% | Power grids, EVs, AI data centers, renewables |\n22\t| Cobalt | ~$15B | Variable | Volatile | Battery cathodes, superalloys, DRC export quotas |\n23\t| Nickel | ~$40B | Variable | Depressed | Battery cathodes, stainless steel (Indonesian oversupply) |\n24\t| NdFeB Permanent Magnets | ~$20B | ~$35B+ | 10-12% | EV motors (96% of RE magnet demand), wind turbines, defense |\n25\t\n26\t### China's Supply Chain Dominance\n27\t\n28\t| Supply Chain Stage | China's Share | Next Largest Player | Strategic Implication |\n29\t|---|---|---|---|\n30\t| Rare Earth Mining | ~60-70% | Myanmar (~12%) | Diversifiable through Australia, US, Canada |\n31\t| Rare Earth Separation/Refining | ~85-90% | Malaysia (Lynas, ~8%) | True chokepoint; 5-10 years to replicate |\n32\t| Oxide-to-Metal Conversion | ~90%+ | Estonia (Neo, <3%) | Extreme concentration |\n33\t| NdFeB Magnet Manufacturing | ~92% | Japan (~5%) | Near-total monopoly |\n34\t| Heavy REE (Dy, Tb) Processing | ~98% | None at scale | Most critical vulnerability |\n35\t| Gallium Refining | ~98% | None significant | Single point of failure |\n36\t| Battery-Grade Graphite | ~90%+ | None at scale | EV supply chain risk |\n37\t\n38\t### Demand Growth Projections (2025-2035)\n39\t\n40\t| Mineral | 2025 Demand | 2030 Projection | 2035 Projection | Supply Risk |\n41\t|---------|------------|----------------|----------------|-------------|\n42\t| Rare Earth Oxides (total) | ~200,000 MT | ~300,000-400,000 MT | ~400,000-600,000 MT | HIGH |\n43\t| NdPr (Neodymium-Praseodymium) | ~55,000 MT | ~90,000+ MT | ~150,000+ MT | HIGH |\n44\t| Dysprosium | ~2,500 MT | ~4,000+ MT | ~6,000+ MT | CRITICAL |\n45\t| Lithium (LCE) | ~1.0M MT | ~2.0M+ MT | ~3.5M+ MT | HIGH |\n46\t| Copper | 28M MT | ~33M MT | ~37M+ MT | CRITICAL |\n47\t| Cobalt | ~200,000 MT | ~280,000 MT | ~350,000 MT | MEDIUM |\n48\t\n49\t## Key Sectors\n50\t\n51\t### 1. Mining & Extraction: The Resource Base\n52\t\n53\tThe mining tier is the most geographically diversified stage of the critical minerals supply chain. Australia, the United States, Canada, Chile, and the DRC all hold world-class deposits. The investment challenge is that mining alone does not confer strategic value -- the processing bottleneck downstream determines who captures margin.\n54\t\n55\t**Rare Earth Mining** is dominated by MP Materials (Mountain Pass, California) and Lynas (Mt Weld, Australia) outside China. MP produced a record 721 MT of NdPr in Q3 2025 (+51% YoY) and ceased all sales to China under a DoD agreement. Lynas targets 10,500-12,000 t/year NdPr capacity. Energy Fuels (UUUU) offers dual uranium/rare earth exposure processing monazite sands at its White Mesa Mill, with commercial Dy/Tb production targeted for Q4 2026. The pipeline includes Iluka's government-backed Eneabba refinery (from 2027), Arafura's Nolans Project (4,440 t/year NdPr), and Vital Metals' Nechalacho mine in Canada.\n56\t\n57\t**Lithium Mining** recovered from the brutal \"Lithium Winter\" of 2024-2025 when lithium carbonate crashed from ~$80,000/tonne to under $10,000/tonne. Prices stabilized around $18,500/tonne by early 2026. Albemarle ($19.2B market cap) achieved $450M in cost savings and is restarting its historic Kings Mountain mine in North Carolina. SQM ($20.4B) operates the world's lowest-cost brine operations in Chile's Atacama and is expanding to 240,000 MT Li2CO3 + 100,000 MT LiOH under a new partnership with state-owned Codelco through 2060. Lithium Americas (LAC) is constructing Phase 1 of Thacker Pass in Nevada (40,000 t/year, $1.97B DOE loan, GM partnership), targeting late 2027 mechanical completion. Rio Tinto's $6.7B acquisition of Arcadium Lithium gives it a dominant Argentine brine portfolio targeting 200,000+ t/year by 2028.\n58\t\n59\t**Copper Mining** faces a structural deficit starting 2026, with ICSG projecting a 150,000-tonne shortfall and J.P. Morgan estimating 330,000 MT. Freeport-McMoRan (FCX, $87.2B) produced 3.4B lbs of copper in FY2025, with the critical near-term catalyst being the phased restart of Grasberg (Indonesia) in Q2 2026 -- expected to reach 1.6B lbs Cu/year for 2027-2029. Southern Copper (SCCO, $154.6B) holds the industry's largest copper reserve base (>112B lbs) and is advancing the Tia Maria project in Peru (120,000 t/year by late 2026/early 2027).\n60\t\n61\t**Cobalt** saw a dramatic reversal when the DRC's February 2025 export ban and subsequent quota system (96,000 MT/year -- roughly half of 2024 volumes) drove cobalt prices from ~$21,500/tonne to ~$56,400/tonne (+162%). CMOC (Chinese-owned) and Glencore dominate DRC production, controlling ~46% of global output combined.\n62\t\n63\t### 2. Processing & Refining: The Strategic Chokepoint\n64\t\n65\tProcessing is where geopolitical leverage concentrates. China controls 85-90% of rare earth refining and has built this dominance over three decades through strategic underpricing (1990s), vertical integration (2000s), and export control weaponization (2010s-present). Approximately 70% of rare earth separation patents are held by Chinese entities.\n66\t\n67\t**The Western Processing Gap** is severe. Current non-Chinese rare earth separation capacity covers approximately 15,000 MT/year of light REEs (NdPr) against 60,000 MT demand (-75% gap), zero heavy REE separation at scale against 4,000 MT demand (-100% gap), and approximately 2,500 MT/year of NdFeB magnets against 25,000 MT demand (-90% gap). Closing this gap requires an estimated $15-25B in investment through 2035.\n68\t\n69\tKey Western processing initiatives include MP Materials' Independence magnet facility in Fort Worth (1,000 MT initial, scaling to 10,000 MT via the 10-X facility by ~2028, backed by $400M DOD equity + $150M OSC loan + $1B construction financing); USA Rare Earth's Stillwater, Oklahoma facility (1,200 MT initial, scaling to 5,000 MT, backed by $1.6B CHIPS Act funding); Neo Performance Materials' Narva, Estonia magnet plant (Europe's first, ramping 2026); and Ucore's RapidSX technology (3x conventional SX efficiency, Louisiana deployment mid-2026). Lynas's Texas heavy REE facility -- the only planned non-Chinese heavy rare earth separator at scale -- faces an uncertain future after stalling amid \"America First\" policy shifts favoring domestic competitors.\n70\t\n71\t**Recycling** represents a critical complementary pathway. Current global rare earth recycling rates are below 1%, but manufacturing scrap recycling (20-40% of magnet material is wasted during production) offers near-term opportunity. Cyclic Materials (private, $75M Series C) is the most advanced pure-play rare earth magnet recycler, building a 2,000-6,000 t/year campus in South Carolina. Redwood Materials (private, ~$5-6B valuation) leads battery recycling with 100 GWh capacity targeted by 2025.\n72\t\n73\t### 3. Defense & Industrial Demand: The Non-Negotiable Consumer\n74\t\n75\tThe U.S. military consumes 3,000-4,000 tons of rare earth magnets annually. Every major weapons platform depends on materials overwhelmingly sourced from China:\n76\t\n77\t| Platform | Rare Earth Content | Key Materials |\n78\t|----------|-------------------|---------------|\n79\t| F-35 Lightning II | ~920 lbs (417 kg) per aircraft | NdFeB magnets, SmCo magnets (~50 lbs), Dy, Tb, Y |\n80\t| Virginia-class Submarine | ~9,200 lbs (4.2 MT) per boat | Terfenol-D (sonar), SmCo (propulsion), Nd (navigation) |\n81\t| Precision-Guided Munitions | SmCo magnets per unit | SmCo irreplaceable for high-temp guidance (up to 300C) |\n82\t| Night Vision Systems | Up to 50% lanthanum by weight | Lanthanum oxide glass for high-refractive optics |\n83\t| Jet Engines (F135) | Rhenium superalloys, YSZ coatings | Rhenium, yttrium, hafnium |\n84\t\n85\tThe EV sector drives the largest volume demand, with permanent magnet motors representing 86%+ of EV traction motors. At 0.7 kg NdPr oxide per vehicle, 30 million EVs by 2030 would require ~21,000 MT NdPr oxide annually -- roughly 50% of current global production. Wind turbines add substantial demand: a single GE Haliade-X 13 MW offshore turbine requires 4-6 MT of NdFeB magnets. AI data center copper demand is projected to grow from 1.1M MT (2025) to 2.5M MT (2040).\n86\t\n87\tThe U.S. government response has been historic: $2B for National Defense Stockpile expansion, $5B Industrial Base Fund, $400M direct equity in MP Materials (making DOD the largest shareholder), $550M total DOD investment in MP, and $1.6B CHIPS Act funding for USA Rare Earth. Combined allied investment (US, Australia, Canada, EU, Japan) exceeds $25 billion committed through 2030.\n88\t\n89\t### 4. China & Geopolitics: The Catalyst and the Risk\n90\t\n91\tChina has systematically weaponized mineral dominance since July 2023, following a consistent escalation ladder: licensing requirements, tightened licensing, country-specific bans, technology controls, and extraterritorial application.\n92\t\n93\t**Key Escalation Events:**\n94\t- **July 2023:** Gallium/germanium export controls -- gallium exports fell to effectively zero; prices surged 150%+\n95\t- **August 2024:** Antimony controls -- prices surged 200% within weeks; DRC shipments dropped 97%\n96\t- **April 2025:** Seven heavy rare earths + magnets controlled -- automakers forced to cut production\n97\t- **October 2025:** Most extensive controls to date -- extraterritorial application to products containing Chinese-sourced materials\n98\t- **November 2025:** Temporary suspension until November 2026 -- structural architecture remains intact\n99\t\n100\tThe November 2026 expiry of the U.S.-China trade agreement is the single most important near-term catalyst. Analysts assign 35% probability to continued escalation (all controls reimposed), 45% to managed tension (extended with modifications), and 20% to detente (permanent relaxation).\n101\t\n102\tChina's Belt and Road investments have secured control over DRC cobalt (CMOC = world's largest producer at 114,200 MT in 2024), Indonesian nickel ($30B invested since 2018), Argentine/African lithium (Ganfeng + Tianqi control ~40% of global lithium production access), and Guinea bauxite (70% of exports to China). The IRA's Foreign Entity of Concern (FEOC) rules, with escalating critical mineral thresholds reaching 80% by 2027, are progressively squeezing Chinese minerals out of qualifying U.S. EV supply chains.\n103\t\n104\t## Public Company Analysis\n105\t\n106\t### Comprehensive Ticker Table\n107\t\n108\t| Company | Ticker | Market Cap | Key Metric | Supply Chain Position | Conviction |\n109\t|---------|--------|------------|------------|----------------------|------------|\n110\t| MP Materials | MP | $10.0B | Record 721 MT NdPr (Q3); DOD largest shareholder | Mine-to-Magnet (US) | Tier 1 |\n111\t| Lynas Rare Earths | LYC.AX / LYSCF | ~$10B | Revenue doubling FY2026E to A$1.1B | Mine + Separation (AU/MY) | Tier 1 |\n112\t| Freeport-McMoRan | FCX | $87.2B | 3.4B lbs Cu FY2025; Grasberg restart Q2 2026 | Copper mining (global) | Tier 1 |\n113\t| Albemarle | ALB | $19.2B | $4.9B revenue; Kings Mountain restart | Lithium mining (global) | Tier 1 |\n114\t| SQM | SQM | $20.4B | Lowest-cost lithium; Codelco JV through 2060 | Lithium brine (Chile) | Tier 2 |\n115\t| Southern Copper | SCCO | $154.6B | >112B lbs reserves; $4.3B net income | Copper mining (Mexico/Peru) | Tier 2 |\n116\t| Energy Fuels | UUUU | $5.0B | Dual uranium/REE; ~$1B war chest | REE + Uranium processing (US) | Tier 2 |\n117\t| Pilbara Minerals | PLS.AX | ~A$13B | 754,600 t SC record FY2025; declining costs | Lithium hard-rock (AU) | Tier 2 |\n118\t| Rio Tinto (Arcadium) | RIO | $130B+ | Targeting >200K t LCE by 2028 | Diversified mining + lithium | Tier 2 |\n119\t| USA Rare Earth | USAR | ~$1.5B | $1.6B CHIPS Act; pre-revenue | Magnet manufacturing (US) | Tier 2 |\n120\t| Lithium Americas | LAC | $1.6B | $1.97B DOE loan; GM offtake; late 2027 completion | Lithium development (US) | Tier 3 |\n121\t| Neo Performance | NEO.TO | ~$0.5B | Narva EU magnet plant ramping 2026 | Separation + Magnets (EU) | Tier 3 |\n122\t| Iluka Resources | ILU.AX | ~A$5B | A$1.65B govt financing; Eneabba from 2027 | REE refining (AU) | Tier 3 |\n123\t| Perpetua Resources | PPTA | ~$1B | Only significant US antimony deposit | Antimony/Gold (US) | Tier 3 |\n124\t| Ucore Rare Metals | UCU.V | ~$60M | RapidSX tech; Louisiana mid-2026 | Separation technology (US) | Tier 3 |\n125\t| Vital Metals | VML.AX | ~A$200M | 636,000 t NdPr resource; PFS 2026 | REE mining (Canada) | Tier 3 |\n126\t| TMRC | TMRC | <$50M | $1.6B LOI; severe dilution risk | Heavy REE development (US) | Tier 3 |\n127\t\n128\t### Key Private Companies\n129\t\n130\t| Company | Valuation | Focus | Strategic Significance |\n131\t|---------|-----------|-------|----------------------|\n132\t| Redwood Materials | ~$5-6B | Battery recycling | Largest US battery recycler; Tesla co-founder JB Straubel |\n133\t| Cyclic Materials | Private ($75M Series C) | RE magnet recycling | Most advanced pure-play RE recycler; MIT Top 10 Climate Tech |\n134\t| REEtec | Private (LKAB-backed) | REE separation | 720 t/yr NdPr; 90% lower CO2; Scandinavian supply chain |\n135\t\n136\t## Investment Timing Framework\n137\t\n138\t### Near-Term (0-6 months): Catalysts and Events\n139\t\n140\t- **MP Materials magnet revenue ramp** -- Q4 2025 and Q1 2026 earnings should show inflection toward profitability from magnetics segment\n141\t- **Freeport Grasberg restart** -- Phased restart in Q2 2026 is the most important near-term catalyst for copper exposure\n142\t- **USA Rare Earth initial production** -- Commercial production of first 1,200 t/year magnet line targeted H1 2026\n143\t- **DRC cobalt quota impact** -- Watch for inventory drawdowns and price sustainment above $50,000/tonne\n144\t- **Lithium price trajectory** -- $18,500/tonne stabilization needs confirmation; watch SQM and ALB Q1 2026 guidance\n145\t- **Southern Copper Tia Maria commissioning** -- Mining license received late 2025; construction milestones through 2026\n146\t\n147\t### Mid-Term (6-18 months): Structural Shifts\n148\t\n149\t- **November 2026 U.S.-China trade agreement expiry** -- THE catalyst event. Reimposition of October 2025 controls would be massively bullish for Western miners, bearish for China-dependent manufacturers\n150\t- **IRA FEOC threshold increase to 70%** (2026) then 80% (2027) -- progressively disqualifies vehicles with Chinese mineral inputs\n151\t- **Copper structural deficit deepening** -- 2026 deficit of 150,000-330,000 MT should support price appreciation toward $11,000-13,500/tonne (BoA forecast)\n152\t- **MP Materials 10-X facility construction progress** -- Multi-billion dollar magnet factory; commissioning ~2028\n153\t- **Ucore Louisiana RapidSX deployment** -- Modular separation technology validation at commercial scale\n154\t- **Energy Fuels commercial Dy/Tb production** -- Q4 2026 target for 48 MT/year Dy + 14 MT/year Tb\n155\t\n156\t### Long-Term (2-5 years): Secular Trends\n157\t\n158\t- **Western processing share climbing from ~10% to ~20-25%** -- Multiple separation and magnet facilities reaching scale by 2028-2030\n159\t- **EV rare earth demand approaching 21,000 MT NdPr/year** at 30M units by 2030 (~50% of current global NdPr production)\n160\t- **Recycling volumes becoming meaningful** -- First-generation EV motor scrap available from 2030s; manufacturing scrap recycling scaling sooner\n161\t- **Copper supply-demand gap widening** -- S&P Global warns of potential 10M MT deficit by 2040\n162\t- **Lithium market rebalancing** -- New mines (Thacker Pass, Kings Mountain, James Bay) reaching production\n163\t- **Heavy rare earth independence (partial)** -- MP heavy REE circuit, potential Lynas Texas, Ucore separation providing first non-Chinese Dy/Tb at scale\n164\t- **NdFeB magnet reshoring** -- Combined US capacity of 15,000+ MT/year from MP + USA Rare Earth by late 2020s\n165\t\n166\t## Risk Factors\n167\t\n168\t1. **China price manipulation (SEVERITY: HIGH)** -- China can flood markets with cheap minerals to undermine Western investment economics, reprising the 1990s strategy that destroyed the original Mountain Pass mine. The November 2025 control suspension may serve this purpose.\n169\t\n170\t2. **Commodity price volatility (SEVERITY: HIGH)** -- The lithium market demonstrated extreme cyclicality (lithium carbonate from $80,000 to under $10,000 in 18 months). NdPr, copper, and cobalt face similar boom-bust risks.\n171\t\n172\t3. **Execution risk on processing projects (SEVERITY: HIGH)** -- Nearly every Western rare earth project has experienced delays and cost overruns. The Lynas Texas stall, Li-Cycle Rochester Hub pause ($475M+ overruns), and repeated timeline extensions suggest 2028-2030 targets may slip.\n173\t\n174\t4. **Technology gap vs. Chinese operations (SEVERITY: MEDIUM)** -- Western facilities remain 5-10 years behind Chinese operations in process optimization and yield. Chinese SX plants operate at 35,000 MT/year; Western facilities at 2,000-5,000 MT.\n175\t\n176\t5. **Policy discontinuity (SEVERITY: MEDIUM)** -- Western rare earth strategy depends on sustained government support across multiple election cycles. A shift in priorities could strand partially built facilities.\n177\t\n178\t6. **EV demand uncertainty (SEVERITY: MEDIUM)** -- If EV adoption slows or rare-earth-free motor technologies (switched reluctance, wound-rotor) gain traction faster than projected, rare earth demand growth could disappoint. Currently ~95% of EV motors still use rare earth magnets, but Tesla and others are developing alternatives.\n179\t\n180\t7. **Permitting and social license risk (SEVERITY: MEDIUM)** -- Despite Trump administration NEPA reform (14-day EA reviews), mining projects face litigation, community opposition, and environmental challenges. Southern Copper's Tia Maria took years of opposition; Lynas Texas stalled on wastewater permitting.\n181\t\n182\t8. **Nickel oversupply (SEVERITY: HIGH for nickel-exposed names)** -- Indonesian production drives a structural surplus of ~212,000-288,000 tonnes through 2026. Nickel-exposed miners face continued price pressure until Indonesian production cuts materialize.\n183\t\n184\t9. **Geopolitical escalation beyond minerals (SEVERITY: LOW PROBABILITY / HIGH IMPACT)** -- Taiwan Strait crisis would trigger immediate mineral supply disruption, cascading industrial shutdowns, and potential 30-40% drop in global EV production within 3 months.\n185\t\n186\t10. **Valuation compression risk (SEVERITY: MEDIUM)** -- MP Materials (+230% in 2025, $10B market cap), Lynas (+160%, ~$10B), and other Western miners already price in substantial growth. Any execution stumbles or demand disappointments could trigger sharp corrections.\n187\t\n188\t## Recommended Watchlist\n189\t\n190\t| Tier | Ticker | Company | Rationale |\n191\t|------|--------|---------|-----------|\n192\t| **Tier 1** | **MP** | MP Materials | Only integrated US mine-to-magnet; $400M DOD equity; 10-X facility represents US magnet independence; record NdPr production |\n193\t| **Tier 1** | **LYC.AX / LYSCF** | Lynas Rare Earths | Largest non-Chinese REE producer; revenue doubling; only company with non-Chinese Dy production at any scale |\n194\t| **Tier 1** | **FCX** | Freeport-McMoRan | Premier copper play; Grasberg restart catalyst; structural copper deficit from 2026; $87B scale |\n195\t| **Tier 1** | **ALB** | Albemarle | World's largest lithium producer; cost restructuring complete; Kings Mountain restart; institutional-grade lithium exposure |\n196\t| **Tier 2** | **SQM** | SQM | Lowest-cost global lithium; massive expansion; Codelco JV through 2060; Chilean sovereign risk premium |\n197\t| **Tier 2** | **UUUU** | Energy Fuels | Unique dual uranium/REE exposure; $1B war chest; commercial Dy/Tb by Q4 2026; US policy beneficiary |\n198\t| **Tier 2** | **SCCO** | Southern Copper | Industry's largest copper reserves (>112B lbs); $4.3B net income; Tia Maria catalyst; premium valuation |\n199\t| **Tier 2** | **PLS.AX** | Pilbara Minerals | Pure-play hard-rock lithium; declining costs; record production; BMX price discovery platform |\n200\t| **Tier 2** | **USAR** | USA Rare Earth | $1.6B CHIPS Act backing; US magnet manufacturing; Round Top heavy REE deposit; pre-revenue risk |\n201\t| **Tier 3** | **LAC** | Lithium Americas | Largest US lithium project; $1.97B DOE loan + GM backing; high-optionality pre-production play |\n202\t| **Tier 3** | **NEO.TO** | Neo Performance | Only EU rare earth separator and magnet maker; Narva plant; diversified revenue base |\n203\t| **Tier 3** | **ILU.AX** | Iluka Resources | A$1.65B government-backed; Australia's first integrated REE refinery; 2027+ production |\n204\t| **Tier 3** | **PPTA** | Perpetua Resources | Only significant US antimony deposit; antimony prices +200%; DPA Title III support; permitting risk |\n205\t| **Tier 3** | **UCU.V** | Ucore Rare Metals | Proprietary RapidSX separation (3x efficiency); modular deployment; micro-cap risk |\n206\t| **Tier 3** | **TMRC** | Texas Mineral Resources | $1.6B government LOI; heavy REE optionality; severe dilution risk; speculative only |\n207\t\n208\t## Sources & References\n209\t\n210\t### Mining & Extraction\n211\t- MP Materials Q3 2025 Results (investors.mpmaterials.com)\n212\t- MP Materials 230% gain in 2025 (Yahoo Finance)\n213\t- Lynas Rare Earths Full Year 2025 Results (weblink.com.au)\n214\t- Energy Fuels Heavy REE Oxide Production (investors.energyfuels.com, Jul-Sep 2025)\n215\t- Albemarle 2026 Rebound Analysis (markets.financialcontent.com)\n216\t- Rio Tinto Arcadium Lithium Acquisition (riotinto.com, Mar 2025)\n217\t- SQM Q3 2025 Record Lithium Sales (investing.com)\n218\t- Pilbara Minerals Record FY2025 Production (investingnews.com)\n219\t- Lithium Americas Thacker Pass Q3 2025 (lithiumamericas.com)\n220\t- Freeport-McMoRan Q4 2025 Results (q4cdn.com)\n221\t- Southern Copper Tia Maria Progress (simplywall.st)\n222\t- ICSG Copper Surplus/Deficit Projections (miningweekly.com)\n223\t- J.P. Morgan Copper Market Outlook (jpmorgan.com)\n224\t- DRC Cobalt Export Quotas (spglobal.com)\n225\t- Cobalt Price Surge 2025 (fastmarkets.com)\n226\t\n227\t### Processing & Refining\n228\t- IEA Global Critical Minerals Outlook 2025 (iea.org)\n229\t- CSIS Developing Rare Earth Processing Hubs (csis.org)\n230\t- MP Materials DOD Partnership (investors.mpmaterials.com, Jul 2025)\n231\t- Columbia CGEP MP Materials Deal Analysis (energypolicy.columbia.edu)\n232\t- Lynas US Project Updates (lynasrareearths.com)\n233\t- USA Rare Earth CHIPS Funding (okenergytoday.com, Jan 2026)\n234\t- Neo Performance Estonia Magnet Plant (neomaterials.com)\n235\t- Ucore RapidSX Technology (ucore.com)\n236\t- Solvay La Rochelle Rare Earths (solvay.com)\n237\t- REEtec Norway Separation Plant (magneticsmag.com)\n238\t- DOE Critical Minerals Program (energy.gov)\n239\t- Cyclic Materials South Carolina Campus (businesswire.com, Jan 2026)\n240\t- Redwood Materials Overview (redwoodmaterials.com)\n241\t\n242\t### Defense & Industrial Demand\n243\t- U.S. Army Elemental Issue (army.mil)\n244\t- CRS Rare Earth Elements in National Defense (fas.org)\n245\t- Pentagon $1B Critical Minerals Stockpile (mining-technology.com)\n246\t- DOD MP Materials Partnership (war.gov)\n247\t- IDTechEx Rare Earth Magnet Market (idtechex.com)\n248\t- S&P Global Copper in the Age of AI (spglobal.com)\n249\t- Minerals Security Partnership (state.gov)\n250\t- 2026 Critical Minerals Ministerial (state.gov, Feb 2026)\n251\t- US-Australia Critical Minerals Framework (whitehouse.gov, Oct 2025)\n252\t- Canada $6.4B Critical Minerals Investment (carboncredits.com)\n253\t- EU Critical Raw Materials Act (ec.europa.eu)\n254\t- IEA Supply-Demand Gap Analysis (iea.org)\n255\t\n256\t### China & Geopolitics\n257\t- CSIS China Gallium Supply Chain Threat (csis.org)\n258\t- CSIS Antimony Export Restrictions Impact (csis.org)\n259\t- CSIS Most Stringent Export Restrictions (csis.org)\n260\t- China Pauses Rare Earth Export Curbs (fdd.org, Nov 2025)\n261\t- White House U.S.-China Trade Deal (whitehouse.gov, Nov 2025)\n262\t- IRA Section 30D / FEOC Rules (federalregister.gov; congress.gov)\n263\t- Goldman Sachs Geopolitics of Critical Mineral Supply Chains (goldmansachs.com)\n264\t- Atlantic Council Critical Minerals Stress Testing (atlanticcouncil.org)\n265\t- Carnegie Securing America's Critical Minerals Supply (carnegieendowment.org)\n266\t- Fortune Critical Minerals Race (fortune.com, Dec 2025)\n267\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q8Kwt517HqYVMRhJgQ1kZ1","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"c2fc5925-8f0b-4045-82ac-df67363475ba","timestamp":"2026-05-31T23:01:34.321Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Commodities & forex research"}
