{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WYWtGST8C6ZvqVhtuBMjHd","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"April PCE inflation report May 28 2026 core PCE 3.3% personal income spending\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Personal Consumption Expenditures Price Index | U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)\",\"url\":\"https://www.bea.gov/data/personal-consumption-expenditures-price-index\"},{\"title\":\"Personal Consumption Expenditures Price Index, Excluding Food and Energy | U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)\",\"url\":\"https://www.bea.gov/data/personal-consumption-expenditures-price-index-excluding-food-and-energy\"},{\"title\":\"Fed's Favorite Inflation Gauge Hits 3.8%, Highest Since May 2023 - Benzinga\",\"url\":\"https://www.benzinga.com/markets/macro-economic-events/26/05/52835775/us-pce-inflation-report-april-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Personal Income and Outlays, April 2026 | U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)\",\"url\":\"https://www.bea.gov/news/2026/personal-income-and-outlays-april-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Boyle Statement on April 2026 PCE Inflation Data | House Budget Committee Democrats\",\"url\":\"https://democrats-budget.house.gov/news/press-releases/boyle-statement-april-2026-pce-inflation-data\"},{\"title\":\"Core inflation hit an annual rate of 3.3% in April, as expected, Fed’s preferred gauge shows\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/28/core-inflation-hit-an-annual-rate-of-3point3percent-in-april-as-expected-feds-preferred-gauge-shows-.html\"},{\"title\":\"Personal Consumption Expenditures Excluding Food and Energy (Chain-Type Price Index) (PCEPILFE) | FRED | St. Louis Fed\",\"url\":\"https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/PCEPILFE\"},{\"title\":\"Median PCE Inflation\",\"url\":\"https://www.clevelandfed.org/indicators-and-data/median-pce-inflation\"},{\"title\":\"Trimmed Mean PCE Inflation rate, April 2026\",\"url\":\"https://www.dallasfed.org/research/pce\"}]\n\nHere are the search results for the April 2026 PCE inflation report released on May 28, 2026:\n\n## Key Inflation Figures\n\nYear-over-year, headline PCE accelerated from 3.5% to 3.8%, matching expectations and marking the highest reading since May 2023.\n\nOn an annual basis, core PCE edged up from 3.2% in March to 3.3%, matching estimates and marking the highest reading since October 2023.\n\n## Monthly Changes\n\nThe headline PCE price index rose 0.4% on the month, falling short of the 0.5% forecast and decelerating from March's 0.7% increase.\n\nThe core PCE price index which strips out food and energy, rose 0.2% month-over-month in April, missing the 0.3% consensus and decelerating from March's 0.3% print.\n\n## Personal Income and Spending\n\nPersonal income decreased less than $0.1 billion (less than 0.1 percent at a monthly rate) in April, and disposable personal income (DPI) decreased $19.9 billion (0.1 percent), while personal consumption expenditures (PCE) increased $111.1 billion (0.5 percent).\n\nPersonal saving was $611.7 billion in April, and the personal saving rate—personal saving as a percentage of DPI—was 2.6 percent.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JPmvo8LP7wReL3gw7pS53N","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"63f4cc14-8e27-4ef8-90bf-3a0c6d3c15b6","timestamp":"2026-05-31T23:04:11.634Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Rates, credit & Fed research"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0124qp8aH7FMGat7AjxekxC1","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Kevin Warsh Fed chair comments May 2026 monetary policy inflation hawkish\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Kevin Warsh sworn in as Fed chair as inflation worries raise the volume on possible rate hikes\",\"url\":\"https://finance.yahoo.com/economy/policy/article/kevin-warsh-confirmed-new-fed-chair-as-inflation-kicks-higher-complicating-the-central-banks-path-164303609.html\"},{\"title\":\"Opinion | Fed chair Kevin Warsh will confront a critical question on inflation - The Washington Post\",\"url\":\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2026/05/20/fed-chair-kevin-warsh-will-confront-critical-question-inflation/\"},{\"title\":\"18 Words From Fed Chair Kevin Warsh That Could Keep Interest Rates Higher for Years - 24/7 Wall St.\",\"url\":\"https://247wallst.com/investing/2026/05/31/18-words-from-fed-chair-kevin-warsh-that-could-keep-interest-rates-higher-for-years/\"},{\"title\":\"Warsh at the Reins: New Fed Chair Faces Challenges | Charles Schwab\",\"url\":\"https://www.schwab.com/learn/story/are-you-there-inflation-its-me-kevin-warsh\"},{\"title\":\"Kevin Warsh Wants to Change How You Think About Inflation, Which May Be Terrible News for Wall Street | The Motley Fool\",\"url\":\"https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/05/13/kevin-warsh-change-inflation-terrible-news-wall-st/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what Kevin Warsh has been saying about monetary policy and inflation in May 2026:\n\n## Key Comments on Inflation\n\nKevin Warsh, the new Federal Reserve chair, has signaled that inflation victory requires public perception to shift beyond pricing concerns, not just reaching a 2% target, potentially keeping interest rates elevated longer than markets expect. During his confirmation hearing, Warsh said the US economy is still dealing with ripples from a pandemic-driven spike in inflation and that the Fed needs a different framework for assessing it.\n\n## Hawkish Stance\n\nWith inflation still elevated, Warsh may face challenges in his goals for rate cuts, with inflation above 2% making that difficult. Reducing interest rates from the current range of 3.5% to 3.75% is probably the goal most often associated with Warsh, but with inflation still elevated, that may be his biggest challenge.\n\nCME FedWatch Tool shows almost no chance for a 2026 rate cut and—after the recent bearish April Consumer Price Index (CPI) and Producer Price Index (PPI)—factors in a much higher chances of an inflation-fighting rate hike.\n\n## Broader Policy Outlook\n\nWarsh said during his confirmation hearing that he wants \"messier\" interest rate-setting meetings, where a \"good family fight\" can lead to better economic decisions. Kevin Warsh is officially the chairman of the Federal Reserve, sworn in on Friday.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JPmvo8LP7wReL3gw7pS53N","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"75bbb944-f0e0-420d-affa-3b7b37e0abb4","timestamp":"2026-05-31T23:04:13.188Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Rates, credit & Fed research"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016D7JPQVMuAZ4RBtoqyJAX8","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"May 30\" OR \"May 31\" 2026 Iran US peace deal markets Treasury Fed weekend\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"US x Iran permanent peace deal by...? Predictions & Odds 2026 | Polymarket\",\"url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/us-x-iran-permanent-peace-deal-by\"},{\"title\":\"Treasury yields slide after Memorial Day break as traders weigh Iran peace prospects\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/26/treasury-yields-us-strikes-on-iran-oil-bonds.html\"},{\"title\":\"US x Iran diplomatic meeting by...? Trading Odds & Predictions 2026 | Polymarket\",\"url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/us-x-iran-diplomatic-meeting-by-329\"},{\"title\":\"Treasury yields tick lower as investors stay optimistic on Iran peace deal prospects despite U.S. strikes\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/27/treasury-yields-investor-optimism-ceasefire-prospects-rise.html\"},{\"title\":\"Treasurys hold steady after yields fall on U.S.-Iran ceasefire talks\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/amp/2026/05/29/treasurys-hold-steady-after-yields-fall-on-us-iran-ceasefire-talks.html\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what happened regarding Iran-US peace deal negotiations and markets around May 30-31, 2026:\n\n## Iran-US Peace Deal Progress\n\nOn May 30, 2026, President Trump held a two-hour meeting with aides to decide on moving forward with an Iran deal but did not announce a decision. On May 23, 2026, top negotiators from the US and Iran approved a draft peace deal, which was sent to leaders of both nations for final approval.\n\nReports indicated that Washington and Tehran have largely agreed on the terms of a 60-day memorandum of understanding to extend the ceasefire, though the deal still needs sign-off from President Donald Trump.\n\n## Market and Treasury Reaction\n\nThe markets responded positively to peace deal prospects during this period. Treasury yields fell as bond markets returned from a Memorial Day break to bolstered hopes of a Middle East peace deal, with the 10-year U.S. Treasury note yield moving lower by more than 8 basis points to 4.489%.\n\nOil prices fell as traders hoped for progress on peace negotiations, with Brent crude futures closing down 5.31% to $94.29 per barrel.\n\n## Market Sentiment\n\nThe peace negotiations had created significant market volatility. The foreign minister's visit was seen as a concrete step toward a diplomatic resolution, briefly stabilizing market sentiment for the May 31 outcome, though the imminent expiry of the ceasefire without a fresh agreement reinforced market pessimism, pushing prices down to their lowest levels for the May-31 deadline.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JPmvo8LP7wReL3gw7pS53N","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"61d391c5-f1f7-4c4f-93cd-2e31266ed0ef","timestamp":"2026-05-31T23:04:13.450Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Rates, credit & Fed research"}
