{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VZcjeS5jfvDyJzCyKAq9Pc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Report written to `/home/bigpic/projects/bigpic-markets/eagle-eye/W22_2026-05-31/04_crypto_alternative.md`.\n\nThe week was decisively risk-off: US airstrikes on Iran near the Strait of Hormuz on 5/28 sent BTC below $73K and triggered ~$1B in liquidations, before truce-extension hopes sparked a partial bounce — Bitcoin sits ~$73,800 this weekend (Sun 5/31), ETH is languishing right on the $2,000 line (ETH/BTC ~0.0272), and BTC dominance has climbed toward ~60% as alts underperform. The dominant flow story was spot Bitcoin ETFs bleeding ~$1.42B over a 10-session outflow streak (longest since 2024), with IBIT alone shedding $527.8M on 5/27; XRP ETFs were a rare inflow bright spot (~$35M) and Stellar (XLM) ripped ~33–50% on DTCC tokenization news. Weekend specifics captured: the contained StablR multisig hack (~$2.8M netted, key-management failure not a major de-peg), stablecoin market cap at a record ~$322B, SEC's Paxos clearing-agency approval, the first US-approved Bitcoin perpetual futures, and Goldman's full exit from XRP/SOL ETFs while holding BTC. File confirmed written."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7302,"cache_read_input_tokens":81556,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":7302,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01PHSkBGNFVsYNfGY6YDTHaK","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"7b271ab2-ef5c-4a60-9140-5d2a61c78567","request_id":"req_011CbbUxyBgfQ23edtxH2WWE","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Crypto & alternative research"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01HDUuXCnQDWAQfr7K99GBej","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a complete, well-sourced picture. Key data confirmed from FRED (authoritative):\n\n**Credit spreads (FRED, through 5/28):**\n- IG OAS (BAMLC0A0CM): 0.74 (5/22) → 0.73 (5/28) = ~73 bps, -1 to -2 bps on week. Historically very tight.\n- HY OAS (BAMLH0A0HYM2): 2.74 (5/22) → 2.72 (5/28) = ~272 bps, ~-2 bps. Peaked at 2.86 on 5/19 (CPI/Iran scare), then tightened.\n- BBB OAS: 0.93, -1 bp.\n\n**Treasuries (FRED, 5/22 → 5/28/29):**\n- 2Y: 4.13 → 3.98 (5/29) = -15 bps\n- 5Y: 4.27 → 4.15 (5/28) = ~-13 bps\n- 10Y: 4.56 → 4.45 (5/29) = -11 bps\n- 30Y: 5.07 → 4.98 (5/28) = ~-9 bps\n- 2s10s: 0.43 (5/22) → 0.47 (5/29) = +4 bps steepening\n- 3m10y: 0.88 (5/22) → 0.76 (5/29) = -12 bps flatter\n\n**Effective fed funds:** 3.62% (target 3.50-3.75%).\n\nThe \"yields rose\" data from my first search was stale/wrong (it conflated the mid-May CPI selloff). The week ending 5/29 was a clear bull rally (yields down) driven by Iran de-escalation and softer MoM PCE.\n\nSovereign ratings: no in-window action; Moody's Aa1 (May 2025) is historical. ON RRP essentially drained (~$1-12B). TGA ~$830B.\n\nI have everything I need. Let me write the report."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3631,"cache_read_input_tokens":78341,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3631,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JPmvo8LP7wReL3gw7pS53N","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"5e00a34f-1a86-4570-a3bd-b315b39a9e41","request_id":"req_011CbbUy2gHFQL7Dn1pJoMRW","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Rates, credit & Fed research"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EAN6s9XRhpX5Ti7MQbHtpM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DexATGzfDDYtpGZK7mjrMN","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/bigpic/projects/bigpic-markets/eagle-eye/W22_2026-05-31/01_equities_sectors.md","content":"# Eagle Eye — Equities & Sectors (Agent 1)\n\n*Point-in-time snapshot as of Sunday, 2026-05-31 (Pacific). Window: trading week ending Friday 2026-05-29, plus weekend breaking news through Sun 5/31.*\n\n---\n\n## Market Overview\n\nUS equities closed the week and the month of May at **record highs**, capping a powerful, AI-led rally that pushed the S&P 500 to its **ninth consecutive weekly gain** — the longest such streak since 2023. The dominant macro driver was the collapse in oil prices on optimism around a US-Iran ceasefire (see Weekend Developments), which removed a major overhang that had built up earlier in 2026 when Strait of Hormuz fears spiked crude.\n\n**Friday 2026-05-29 closing levels (confirmed for that date):**\n\n| Index | Friday 5/29 Close | Friday Daily | Notes |\n|-------|-------------------|--------------|-------|\n| S&P 500 (SPX) | **7,580.06** | +0.22% | New record; 9th straight weekly gain; 7th straight up day |\n| Nasdaq Composite | **26,972.62** | +0.26% | New record |\n| Dow Jones (DJIA) | **51,032.46** | +0.72% (+363 pts) | First-ever close above 51,000 |\n| Russell 2000 (RUT) | **~2,919** | -0.60% | Pulled back from record highs; small-caps lagging |\n\n**Monthly performance (May 2026):** Nasdaq Composite +~8% (leader), S&P 500 +~5%, Dow +~3%. Technology was the best-performing sector since the late-March market lows.\n\n**Context (historical, not this week):** The index level path in 2026 has been volatile — SPX fell from the high-6800s in early March to a low near **6,343** in late March before the rebound carried it back through prior highs to current records. The 200-day MA sits around **6,831** and the 50-day around **7,058**, so price is well extended above both. RSI on the S&P 500 was **~73.6** as of Friday — above the conventional overbought threshold of 70.\n\n**Sunday-night futures (as of Sun 5/31):** Little changed / flat. Dow futures down ~30 points; S&P 500 and Nasdaq 100 futures roughly flat as June trading opens near record highs.\n\n---\n\n## Weekend Developments\n\nMostly quiet on price (futures flat), but several market-moving storylines carried over the weekend:\n\n- **US-Iran 60-day ceasefire MOU (the week's biggest macro catalyst).** US officials told CNBC (Thu 5/28) that negotiators reached a 60-day memorandum of understanding to extend the Iran ceasefire and open talks on Iran's nuclear program; President Trump still had to sign off. This drove **Brent crude down ~19% in May** (worst month since the Covid crash) to **~$93.71** Friday, and **WTI to ~$87.18** (-16.5% MTD), as the market priced in reopened Strait of Hormuz shipping. Falling oil was a key tailwind for the broad equity rally but a headwind for energy producers' forward earnings. Watch for confirmation/signing over the window.\n- **AI mega-cap IPO pipeline heating up (CNBC, Sun 5/31).** SpaceX is reportedly in \"pole position\" to debut **within ~2 weeks** — the only one of the three to have publicly released an S-1. OpenAI is reported to be working on a confidential filing; Anthropic could come public as soon as Q4. This is directly relevant to the Space and AI theses below.\n- **Anthropic ~$1T valuation (CNBC, 5/28).** Anthropic announced a **$65B Series H at a ~$965B valuation** (led by Altimeter, Dragoneer, Greenoaks, Sequoia), surpassing OpenAI as the most valuable AI startup, with a reported **$47B revenue run-rate** (up from ~$30B earlier in 2026). Reinforces the AI software/model-layer thesis and private-market premium.\n- **Week ahead:** Friday's nonfarm payrolls report is the marquee event for Fed-policy read-through.\n\nNo new geopolitical shock, M&A, or guidance bombshell emerged Saturday 5/30–Sunday 5/31 beyond the above.\n\n---\n\n## Sector Performance\n\nWeekly leadership favored **large-cap growth, technology, energy, commodities, and cybersecurity**, with rotation **out of small-caps, value, REITs, and non-US equities**. (Note: sector-by-sector exact weekly % returns were not cleanly available for the 5/25–5/29 window in sources; the rankings below are from relative-strength/RRG analysis and month-to-date data.)\n\n**Sector ranking / relative strength (week of 5/25–5/29, per StockCharts RRG):**\n\n| Rank | Sector (ETF) | Read |\n|------|--------------|------|\n| 1 | Energy (XLE) | Leads the ranking but **consolidating** — relative strength slipping into the weakening quadrant despite YTD dominance |\n| 2 | Technology (XLK) | **Strongest momentum**, no sign of weakness; only sector beating SPX in May (+~10.6% MTD vs SPX +~2.9%) |\n| 3 | Materials (XLB) | Fragile rotation, weakening quadrant |\n| 4 | Consumer Staples (XLP) | Jumped from 6th to 4th, displacing Real Estate; but moving toward lagging quadrant |\n| 5 | Industrials (XLI) | Fragile rotation |\n| 7 | Utilities (XLU) | **May's biggest loser, ~-4.9% MTD** |\n| 8 | Communication Services (XLC) | Lagging |\n| 9 | Consumer Discretionary (XLY) | Lagging |\n| 10 | Health Care (XLV) | Lagging |\n| 11 | Financials (XLF) | **Last place** |\n\n**2026 YTD context:** Energy is the best-performing S&P 500 sector YTD (+~34.5%), with Technology now second. The May oil collapse is a near-term risk to energy's leadership even as the YTD number remains dominant. Utilities' May weakness is notable given the AI/data-center power narrative — likely profit-taking and rate/rotation dynamics rather than a thesis break.\n\n---\n\n## Earnings\n\nA blowout week for AI infrastructure and software names drove the tape:\n\n- **Dell (DELL) — best day on record.** Reported Q1 with adj. EPS **$4.86 vs ~$2.96 est.** and revenue **$43.8B vs ~$35.77B est.** (+~88% YoY), powered by **$24.4B AI orders** and **$16.1B AI server revenue (+757% YoY)**. Raised FY27 guidance sharply (adj. EPS midpoint to **$17.90** from $12.90; revenue to **$165–169B**). Stock closed **$317.05** then jumped ~**33–39% after-hours**; reportedly up ~234% in 2026. Validated the AI server supercycle and the Dell-Palantir \"AI factory\" partnership.\n- **Snowflake (SNOW) — sparked a software rally.** Q1 FY27 revenue **$1.39B (+34% YoY)**, non-GAAP EPS **$0.39** (beat by ~22%), raised FY product-revenue guide to **$5.84B (+31%)**, 13,600+ accounts using AI features.\n- **Palantir (PLTR) +~9–10%** on Friday as Dell's beat validated their AI-factory partnership. (PLTR itself reported earlier in 2026: Q1 revenue +85% to $1.63B, US gov +84%, FY26 guide raised to +71% growth — but stock still **down ~24% YTD** on valuation.)\n- **Zscaler (ZS) — guidance-driven sell-off (week of 5/26).** Q3 revenue **+25% YoY to $850.5M**, ARR **+25% to $3.525B** — both solid — but soft forward guide (FY revenue growth guided to **16–17% vs ~19.5% consensus**) sent the **stock down ~30%** on Wednesday. Dragged **PANW (-~4%)** and **CRWD (-~3%)** intraday; Wedbush's Dan Ives defended both (raised targets to $300 / $700), framing ZS's issue as company-specific execution amid sector consolidation toward PANW/CRWD.\n- **Cameco (CCJ)** reported Q1 2026 on May 5 (historical, not this week) — results consistent with annual expectations.\n\n---\n\n## Breadth & Sentiment\n\n- **Breadth is healthy but not euphoric / participation uneven.** ~**59% of S&P 500 names above their 200-day MA** and ~**54.4% above their 50-day MA** (both at ~39th percentile readings) as of Friday — i.e., a majority in uptrends but well short of a broad-based thrust, consistent with mega-cap tech leadership. New-high expansion was described as only modest.\n- **Volatility:** **VIX closed 15.32 on Friday 5/29** (-2.67% on the day) — a calm, low-fear reading consistent with record highs.\n- **Momentum:** S&P 500 **RSI ~73.6** — overbought; the rally is extended and vulnerable to a pause, especially with the structural calendar noting post-record extension into June.\n- **Flows/sentiment:** Risk-on, rotating toward large-cap growth/tech/energy/commodities/cybersecurity and away from small-caps (RUT down on the week), value, REITs, and non-US.\n- **Structural calendar note (from CALENDAR.md):** June is a major convergence month — FOMC (Jun 17, SEP), Triple Witch + S&P rebalance (Jun 19), Russell reconstitution (Jun 26). Positioning edge historically starts ~Jun 8.\n\n---\n\n## Thesis Watchlist\n\nWeekly price action and catalysts for Tier 1/2 names by sector. Where exact weekly % was unavailable, monthly/YTD context is labeled as such.\n\n**AI Infrastructure** — the week's epicenter.\n- **NVDA:** Up ~18% YTD but **struggled over the prior week** (week of ~5/27) on valuation/profit-taking; still the GPU bellwether. No earnings this week.\n- **AVGO:** Among the best-performing AI names over the trailing 12 months; Q4 2025 revenue +28% YoY. Custom-silicon thesis intact.\n- **DELL (Tier-adjacent / AI server):** Blowout (see Earnings) — best day ever, FY27 guide raised, the single biggest single-stock story of the week.\n- **MU (Micron):** **Best week since 2008, ~+30% over five sessions** on AI/HBM memory demand — standout in the cheap-AI-semi thesis.\n- **AMD:** ~$422, **+~98% YTD**; data-center revenue +57% YoY. Mid-week semis wobble (see below) but strong trend.\n- **MRVL (Marvell):** ~$167, **+~86.9% YTD**, near 52-week high ($182.58); slid ~5.3% intraday mid-month on a sector-wide selloff (Samsung strike risk + TSMC stake-sale headlines + rare-earth supply worries).\n- **TSM:** ~$418, +~31% YTD, +~5% over the past month. A reported **TSMC stake sale** and a **potential Samsung strike** triggered a one-day semis selloff mid-month.\n- **PLTR:** +~9–10% Friday on Dell read-through; -~24% YTD on valuation.\n\n**Cybersecurity** — consolidation winners vs. a casualty.\n- **ZS:** **-~30%** on soft guidance (the sector's negative standout).\n- **PANW / CRWD:** Down ~4% / ~3% intraday in sympathy but defended by the Street as ZS being company-specific; cybersecurity remained a favored flow destination on the week.\n\n**Nuclear / Uranium** — mixed, AI-power narrative intact.\n- **CEG:** +~0.5%; reaffirmed 20-yr Meta/Clinton PPA (1.1 GWe from mid-2027 through 2047).\n- **VST:** Slightly lower; reaffirmed 2026 adj. EBITDA guide $6.8–7.6B on hyperscaler demand.\n- **CCJ:** +~1.9% on the day; **+~25% YTD**, climbed ~6% earlier in May on NRC approval news.\n- **OKLO:** -~1.8% on the day; rallied ~12% earlier in May (May 6) on **NRC Aurora approval**; **SMR (NuScale)** popped ~10% intraday on that news.\n\n**Space** — rotation within the sector ahead of the SpaceX IPO.\n- **LUNR (Intuitive Machines):** +~9% (Thu) — relative-strength leader; **+~166% YTD**.\n- **RKLB:** Choppy/down on the day; **+~106% YTD**; Q1 revenue +64% YoY to ~$200M, **record ~$2.2B backlog**; Neutron debut later in 2026 is the catalyst.\n- **PL (Planet Labs):** -~2% on the day; **+~146% YTD**; RPO surged ~361% to ~$672M on NGA/NRO/NASA/Navy/NATO defense contracts.\n- Sector is seeing profit-taking/rotation as the **SpaceX IPO (expected within ~2 weeks)** approaches and threatens to reprice the group.\n\n**Quantum** — government-funding rip.\n- **IonQ (IONQ), Rigetti (RGTI), D-Wave (QBTS):** Sharp rally the week of 5/22. On the funding-news day, **QBTS +33.4%, RGTI +30.1%, IONQ +12.2%**; IONQ +~23% on the week. Catalyst: **US plan for ~$2B quantum funding incentives + equity stakes (CNBC, May 21)**; D-Wave and Rigetti signed LOIs for ~$100M each under CHIPS. Valuations remain extreme (P/S ~109 / ~836 / ~791) — Motley Fool flagged a \"$931M warning.\"\n\n**Critical Minerals / Rare Earths** — geopolitics-driven.\n- **MP Materials (MP):** **+~30% over the past month** ahead of strong Q1 2026 earnings; magnet sales from the Independence facility expected H2 2026; DOD floor of $110/kg NdPr. The **Trump-Xi summit (Beijing, May 14–15)** put rare earths center-stage; both sides announced (differing) framings of a critical-minerals understanding. Earlier-2026 dynamic: a 45% Q2 rare-earth price hike and \"Project Vault\" ($12B, 60-mineral strategic reserve, Feb).\n\n**Energy Storage / Batteries.**\n- **FLNC (Fluence):** **Surged ~100%** earlier in May after a fiscal-Q2 beat; upgrades from HSBC and Roth on improving profitability and order momentum (incl. hyperscaler master supply agreements). Trading ~$18 area in early/mid-May.\n- **TSLA:** ~$422; Optimus factory buildout underway (Fremont + Giga Texas); ~$2.1B Samsung battery deal headline. Energy-storage growth narrative intact.\n- **QS (QuantumScape):** Solid-state PowerCo/VW collaboration continues; Eagle Line pilot was the early-2026 catalyst.\n\n**Robotics.**\n- **SYM (Symbotic):** ~$47; **$22.7B backlog**, Q2 FY26 revenue +23.1% YoY to ~$676M, 70 systems deployed (vs 46). The \"actually-shipping-revenue\" standout.\n- **ISRG:** ~$421; durable surgical-robotics platform, but a market laggard relative to high-beta robotics names.\n- **TSLA:** humanoid (Optimus) optionality (see above).\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n\n- [Stock Market Today (May 29, 2026): S&P 500 ninth consecutive weekly gain — TheStreet](https://www.thestreet.com/stock-market-today/stock-market-today-dow-jones-sp-500-nasdaq-updates-may-29-2026) (2026-05-29)\n- [Stock market today: Dow, S&P 500, Nasdaq cap winning month with fresh records — Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/markets/live/dow-nasdaq-sp-gain-stock-market-today-friday-may-29-222720284.html) (2026-05-29)\n- [S&P 500 and Nasdaq close at new records, lifted by tech rally — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/27/stock-market-today-live-updates.html) (2026-05-27)\n- [Stock futures flat as June trading begins near record highs — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/31/stock-market-today-live-updates.html) (2026-05-31)\n- [Oil prices turn lower as U.S.-Iran ceasefire extension awaits Trump approval — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/28/oil-prices-us-strikes-in-iran-revive-strait-of-hormuz-turmoil-fears.html) (2026-05-28)\n- [Oil drops 20% from 2026 peak on optimism over U.S.-Iran ceasefire talks — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/29/oil-prices-iran-ceasefire-us-trump-strait-hormuz-energy-costs.html) (2026-05-29)\n- [Brent oil posts biggest monthly loss in six years as market counts on a U.S.-Iran deal — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/29/oil-price-iran-deal-war-ceasefire-trump.html) (2026-05-29)\n- [The Best Five Sectors This Week #67 (week of May 25, 2026) — StockCharts](https://articles.stockcharts.com/article/best-five-stock-market-sectors-for-week-of-may25-2026-67/) (2026-05-25)\n- [The Sectors Leading the Market Into the Final Days of May — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/05/23/the-sectors-leading-the-market-into-the-final-days/) (2026-05-23)\n- [May 2026 Economic and Market Update: New Highs and Old Risks — Crestwood Advisors](https://www.crestwoodadvisors.com/may-2026-economic-and-market-update/) (2026-05)\n- [Dell stock skyrockets 32% for its best day ever as AI server revenue soars — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/29/dell-stock-earnings-ai-servers.html) (2026-05-29)\n- [Dell soars after-hours on blowout results, raised guidance — Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/earnings/dell-soars-after-hours-on-blowout-results-raised-full-year-revenue-guidance-4715307) (2026-05-29)\n- [Palantir Soars as Dell Earnings Beat Validates AI Factory Partnership, Snowflake Lifts Software Rally — 24/7 Wall St.](https://247wallst.com/investing/2026/05/29/palantir-soars-9-as-dell-earnings-beat-validates-their-ai-factory-partnership-snowflake-lifts-software-rally/) (2026-05-29)\n- [Our cyber stocks are falling on a rival's earnings blowup (Zscaler) — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/27/our-cyber-stocks-are-falling-on-a-rivals-earnings-blowup-why-its-not-a-cause-for-concern.html) (2026-05-27)\n- [Cybersecurity stocks are surging. One looks promising into earnings — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/26/cybersecurity-stocks-are-surging-one-looks-promising-into-earnings.html) (2026-05-26)\n- [Top 5 AI Stocks for May 2026: Nvidia, AMD, Broadcom — Blockonomi](https://blockonomi.com/top-5-ai-stocks-for-may-2026-nvidia-nvda-amd-broadcom-lead-investor-watchlist/) (2026-05)\n- [Why Marvell Technology (MRVL) shares are sliding (semis selloff: Samsung strike, TSMC stake sale) — StockStory](https://stockstory.org/us/stocks/nasdaq/mrvl/news/why-up-down/why-marvell-technology-mrvl-shares-are-sliding-today-2) (2026-05-18)\n- [Could These Be the Smartest Stocks to Buy After Taking Profits on AMD and Micron? (Micron best week since 2008) — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/05/29/could-these-be-the-smartest-stocks-to-buy-after-ta/) (2026-05-29)\n- [Oklo Advances 12% on NRC Aurora Approval — 24/7 Wall St.](https://247wallst.com/investing/2026/05/06/oklo-advances-12-on-nrc-aurora-approval-is-this-the-ai-infrastructure-nuclear-play/) (2026-05-06)\n- [Intuitive Machines Rallies 9%, Rocket Lab and Planet Labs Decline — 24/7 Wall St.](https://247wallst.com/investing/2026/05/28/intuitive-machines-rallies-9-rocket-lab-and-planet-labs-decline-in-space-stock-divergence/) (2026-05-28)\n- [Why space stocks like Planet Labs, Rocket Lab, and LUNR are surging this year — Invezz](https://invezz.com/news/2026/05/26/why-space-stocks-like-planet-labs-rocket-lab-and-lunr-are-surging-this-year/) (2026-05-26)\n- [Quantum stocks soar as U.S. plans $2 billion funding incentives and equity stakes — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/21/quantum-stocks--us-taking-equity-stakes.html) (2026-05-21)\n- [Quantum Computing Stocks IonQ, Rigetti, D-Wave $931M Warning — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/05/28/quantum-computing-ionq-rgti-qbts-wall-st-warning/) (2026-05-28)\n- [White House touts deals on soybeans and rare earths after Trump-Xi summit — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/18/us-china-announce-deals-after-trump-xi-summit.html) (2026-05-18)\n- [Trump-Xi summit to tackle China's rare earth dominance — S&P Global](https://www.spglobal.com/energy/en/news-research/latest-news/metals/051326-factbox-trump-xi-summit-to-tackle-chinas-rare-earth-dominance) (2026-05-13)\n- [The Best Rare-Earth Stock to Buy and Hold (MP Materials +30% MTD) — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/05/12/the-best-rare-earth-stock-to-buy-and-hold-for-the/) (2026-05-12)\n- [Fluence Energy Stock Spikes 100% After Earnings Beat — TIKR](https://www.tikr.com/blog/fluence-energy-stock-spikes-100-after-battery-storage-firm-beats-earnings-estimates) (2026-05)\n- [Forget Tesla. The Robotics Company With a $22B Backlog (Symbotic) — 24/7 Wall St.](https://247wallst.com/investing/2026/05/19/forget-tesla-the-robotics-company-actually-shipping-revenue-has-a-22-billion-backlog-and-nobody-is-talking-about-it/) (2026-05-19)\n- [Anthropic tops OpenAI as most valuable AI startup, nears $1 trillion valuation — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/28/anthropic-open-ai-startup-value.html) (2026-05-28)\n- [My guide to the IPOs of SpaceX, OpenAI and Anthropic — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/31/my-guide-to-the-ipos-of-spacex-openai-and-anthropic-including-the-one-i-really-want-to-buy.html) (2026-05-31)\n- [CBOE Volatility Index (^VIX) — Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/%5EVIX/) (2026-05-29)\n- [S&P 500 Market Breadth & Momentum — StreetStats](https://streetstats.finance/markets/breadth-momentum/SP500) (2026-05-29)\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1577,"cache_read_input_tokens":151683,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1577,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_018dZEMFFbxCBMwW5jUrv2aX","session_id":"fe1a4df5-a4ab-4fab-90bd-ba1de175a1ca","uuid":"21efb3b3-6b53-47a7-8